WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6-8 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hello and welcome to 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish

4
00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:17.000
I'm Phil and today we have Hannah joining us again from BBC podcast What In The World

5
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:19.000
Welcome Hannah

6
00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:21.000
A-ville? It is so great to be back here

7
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:27.000
So I'm wondering, do you do things that you think are good for the planet?

8
00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:31.000
Oh, I try but I don't think I do enough

9
00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:35.000
So maybe I cycle more than I drive

10
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:39.000
And I try to recycle things but I should be doing a lot more

11
00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:43.000
But some people think that to deal with climate change

12
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:46.000
We can't just rely on individuals

13
00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Phil, it's not up to you and me

14
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:51.000
We need to actually change the way our economy works

15
00:00:51.000 --> 00:00:54.000
And this is an idea called D-growth

16
00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:57.000
And we've been investigating it at What In The World

17
00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:59.000
And we're going to learn a bit more about it today

18
00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:02.000
But first, our quiz question

19
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:07.000
World leaders promised in 2015 to limit global temperature rises

20
00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:09.000
But what was the limit they agreed to?

21
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:13.000
Was it a 1.5 degree Celsius?

22
00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:16.000
B, 2.5 degree Celsius

23
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
Or C, 3.5 degree Celsius

24
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:22.000
I think I know this one Phil

25
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.000
I think it's 1.5 degree Celsius

26
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Okay, we'll find out the answer later in the program

27
00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:34.000
So Hannah, you've been researching D-growth

28
00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:36.000
What does that mean?

29
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:41.000
Well Phil, traditionally governments have always wanted to grow the economy

30
00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.000
More money, more jobs, more stuff

31
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:49.000
But D-growth is a different way of thinking about things

32
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:53.000
Some people say that to tackle the climate crisis

33
00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:55.000
We need to stop our economies from growing

34
00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:58.000
We need to stop using and making more

35
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:02.000
And focus on using fewer of the earth's natural resources

36
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:05.000
The people who support the idea of D-growth

37
00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Are often called D-growthers

38
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:13.000
Right, okay, so D-growthers argue we should make and use less stuff

39
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:15.000
Yes, mostly

40
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:17.000
It's a little bit more complex than that

41
00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:20.000
And I spoke to BBC journalist Alvaro Alvarez

42
00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:22.000
Who told me more about the idea?

43
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.000
So D-growth is not saying that we need to reduce everything

44
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:30.000
It's saying that we need to decrease some elements of our production

45
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:32.000
That are not beneficial

46
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.000
An example of those elements would be fast-fashion

47
00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:39.000
Private jets, the beef and meat industry

48
00:02:39.000 --> 00:02:42.000
So it's not about decreasing everything

49
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
Alvaro says that D-growthers believe we should reduce

50
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:48.000
Some elements of production

51
00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:51.000
An element of something is a part of something

52
00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:55.000
And according to Alvaro, these elements of production

53
00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Are not believed to be beneficial

54
00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:01.000
If something's beneficial, it's useful or good

55
00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:05.000
One example of a kind of production that D-growthers disagree with

56
00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:07.000
Is fast-fashion

57
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:11.000
Fast-fashion refers to clothes that are made very cheaply and quickly

58
00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:15.000
So that customers can afford to buy new outfits more often

59
00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Exactly

60
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:24.000
And before we go any further, many economists do not think that D-growth is a good idea

61
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:27.000
Some of them argue that it would create more poverty

62
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:33.000
And some economists believe D-growth would actually make it harder to solve the climate crisis

63
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:39.000
For example, Professor Sam Fankhauser, an economist at Cambridge University in the UK

64
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:42.000
Spoke to you on what in the world

65
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:46.000
And he argues that D-growth could limit innovation

66
00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:51.000
I think D-growth underestimates the power of innovation

67
00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:54.000
D-growth underestimates the need for investment

68
00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:58.000
That we need a new technology and a new solutions

69
00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:05.000
And D-growth underestimates the social sort of feasibility of what they propose

70
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:11.000
So Professor Fankhauser thinks that D-growth underestimates many things

71
00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:12.000
Such as innovation

72
00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:18.000
If you underestimate something, you don't understand the true importance or size of it

73
00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:23.000
Another factor that Professor Fankhauser says is underestimated by D-growthers

74
00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:26.000
Is the feasibility of social change

75
00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:31.000
Fesibility means the possibility that something can be achieved

76
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:34.000
It comes from the adjective feasible

77
00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:40.000
For example, I could say that I think it's feasible for us to finish this podcast in six minutes

78
00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:42.000
I think we can do it

79
00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:44.000
Well Phil, we're going to have to get a move on

80
00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:47.000
I think it's time to hear the answer to your quiz question

81
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:52.000
I asked how much world leaders agreed to limit global temperature rises to

82
00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:56.000
The answer is 1.5 degrees Celsius

83
00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:01.000
Which scientists believe is needed to stop the worst impacts of climate change

84
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.000
I got it right

85
00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:07.000
Okay, so let's recap some of the vocabulary we've learned

86
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:14.000
Starting with D-growth, which is the economic idea that we should use and make less stuff

87
00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:17.000
An element of something means a part of something

88
00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:20.000
Beneficial means useful or good

89
00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:24.000
Fast fashion refers to clothes that are made cheaply and quickly

90
00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:26.000
So that people can buy them more often

91
00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:32.000
And if you underestimate something, you don't understand the true importance or size of it

92
00:05:32.000 --> 00:05:36.000
The feasibility of something is the likelihood that it can be achieved

93
00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:41.000
We can also describe something as feasible or unfisable

94
00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:44.000
We can do it, or we can't do it

95
00:05:44.000 --> 00:05:47.000
Phil, once again our six minutes are up

96
00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:51.000
But there is just a little bit more time for me to tell you more about my podcast

97
00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:52.000
What in the world?

98
00:05:52.000 --> 00:05:55.000
We have a new episode every single weekday

99
00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:58.000
And we talk about the news, trending topics

100
00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:05.000
In fact, it's a great place to come and learn some new vocabulary about things that are happening in the world

101
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:13.000
Yes, if you've found this episode interesting, try watching what in the world on YouTube with subtitles to practice your English

102
00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:15.000
There's a link in the notes for this episode

103
00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:20.000
And don't forget to try the quiz and work sheet at BBCLearningEnglish.com

104
00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:24.000
Phil, thank you so much for having me again on six minute English

105
00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:25.000
Bye for now

106
00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:26.000
Bye
